{"id": "27164", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27164", "title": "Flaylan the Orc", "text": "Flaylan the Orc is a female orc who is found in &lt;a href=\"Firkraag%27s%20Maze\"&gt;Firkraag's Maze&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Windspear%20Hills\"&gt;Windspear Hills&lt;/a&gt; area.\nShe's located in the room at the opposite end of the hallway from the kitchen where the &lt;a href=\"Troll%20Cook\"&gt;Troll Cook&lt;/a&gt; is found. &lt;a href=\"Derg%20the%20Orc\"&gt;Derg the Orc&lt;/a&gt; is also in the room. She will give &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; some information about &lt;a href=\"Firkraag\"&gt;Firkraag&lt;/a&gt; in return for sparing her life.\nDialogue.\n\"No kill, no kill!\"\n\"I tell you secrets! Things about place you not know! You get good secret here, I tell you!\"\n\"Firkraag run the place! He hidey-hide in special place with Garren child. He wait in dere for yous to comes.\"\n\"Defenses? Lord Firkraag no need defenses. You silly to think so. We hunt the feed an' guard the home, but he not need us protect him.\""}
{"id": "49123", "revid": "284469", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=49123", "title": "Fledgling Vampire", "text": "A Fledgling Vampire is a previously living being now morphed into an &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt; creature who has only recently been converted into a \"beginning\" vampire form. These creatures can be encountered in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%203\"&gt;Chapter III&lt;/a&gt; and in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II%20Chapter%206\"&gt;Chapter VI&lt;/a&gt; of the \"\" campaign, in the company of their masters and mistresses in Bodhi's Hideout.\nThere are four varieties, all being virtually identical except for minor differences. The Fledgling vampires are the 'cannon fodder' placed into the Chapter Three and Six Bodhi confrontations. The Fledglings in chapter 3 &lt;a href=\"Level%20drain\"&gt;Level drain&lt;/a&gt; 2 experience levels upon a hit, and 3 experience levels in chapter 6.\nIt also appears in \"\", in the &lt;a href=\"Vampire%20Hideout\"&gt;Vampire Hideout&lt;/a&gt; in chapter 10.\nGameplay.\nThese creatures may be struck with normal weapons. They utilize the most common AI script for other in-game vampires, and thus behave in a similar manner as other types. They will fight with their touch attack and attempt &lt;a href=\"Domination%20%28Innate%29\"&gt;Vampire Domination&lt;/a&gt; innate ability at available targets in range. When reduced to zero Hit points the creature goes into \"Gas Cloud Form\" and flees the battlefield. They have a rather low hit point value. \nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; makes several changes to this creature. The Fledglings are now level 8/8 Fighter/Thief class. Their dexterity is raised to 19 and also have a 16 constitution. This means they have an improved Armor Class and 83 Hit Points. An extra half attack per round is also gained. The creature is also assigned the \"Improved Vampires\" default AI script. In addition, it now requires +2 enchanted weapons to hit it. For an overview of the mod's \"Smarter Vampires\" AI and other changes, see the \"Mod content\" section on the &lt;a href=\"Vampire\"&gt;Vampire&lt;/a&gt; page."}
{"id": "8941", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=8941", "title": "Flesh Golem", "text": "Flesh Golems are magical constructs created by mages. \nGameplay.\nThey are immune to normal weapons but can be harmed with any magical weapon. Examples of enchanted missiles include &lt;a href=\"Arrow%20%2B2\"&gt;Arrow +2&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Bullet%20%2B1\"&gt;Bullet +1&lt;/a&gt; and the throwing axe &lt;a href=\"Beruel%27s%20Retort\"&gt;Beruel's Retort +1&lt;/a&gt;. \nTheir morale is harder to break than most enemies in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; and they are immune to elemental cold and electricity damage, resist magic at 100%, and are immune to &lt;a href=\"backstab\"&gt;backstab&lt;/a&gt;. They have a very low &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; as compared to other enemies in the game and may prove a challenge to low or intermediate level parties (Level 1-4).\nHowever, they are susceptible to poison in the original \"Baldur's Gate\" and &lt;a href=\"Bolt%20of%20Biting\"&gt;Bolt of Biting&lt;/a&gt; works very well. They have been given immunity to poison in the . As Flesh golems are 125% resistant to electricity damage, they can actually be healed by that damage form.\nThough they may seem formidable to the inexperienced adventurer, they are in fact the weakest of all golems and mostly appear in several locations in \"Baldur's Gate\" in their Ogrillion form. Because the characters in the &lt;a href=\"The%20Black%20Pits\"&gt;The Black Pits&lt;/a&gt; and are too powerful, they were given an upgrade in appearance to a Clay Golem, which increased their movement rate from 66% to 144%.\nLocations.\nIn \"Baldur's Gate\" they can be found in the &lt;a href=\"High%20Hedge%20Estate\"&gt;High Hedge Estate&lt;/a&gt;, in a &lt;a href=\"Black%20Alaric%27s%20Cave\"&gt;Black Alaric's Cave&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Lighthouse\"&gt;Lighthouse&lt;/a&gt; area, and on &lt;a href=\"Durlag%27s%20Tower%20%28Labyrinth%20Level%20Two%29\"&gt;Labyrinth Level Two&lt;/a&gt; of &lt;a href=\"Durlag%27s%20Tower\"&gt;Durlag's Tower&lt;/a&gt;.\nIn the \"Enhanced Edition\" they are summoned by &lt;a href=\"Baeloth\"&gt;Baeloth&lt;/a&gt; in the final battle in \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Black%20Pits\"&gt;The Black Pits&lt;/a&gt;\" after &lt;a href=\"Ghlouralk\"&gt;Ghlouralk&lt;/a&gt; has been killed.\nIn \"Shadows of Amn\" two flesh golems are found in a secret room on the second floor of the &lt;a href=\"De%27Arnise%20Keep\"&gt;de'Arnise Keep&lt;/a&gt;.\nInside &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep\"&gt;Watcher's Keep&lt;/a&gt; on the &lt;a href=\"Watcher%27s%20Keep%20Altar%20Level\"&gt;Altar Level&lt;/a&gt; there is a &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Manual\"&gt;manual&lt;/a&gt; to be found that can summon a &lt;a href=\"Flesh%20Golem%20%28Manual%29\"&gt;Flesh Golem&lt;/a&gt; once per day to fight for the summoner. \nCombat.\nFlesh golems are equipped with two undroppable items: \nFlesh golems are immune to standard missiles (arrows/bullets) but not immune to magical ones.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; mod and the installation of the \"\"AI Enhancement's\" component improves many aspects of creatures encountered in the game. In regard to golems, the mod implements the following:\nImproved Golems (BG2, BG2EE, BGT/EET)&lt;br&gt;\nThis component doesn't really make golems smarter (they're supposed to be stupid) But it streamlines their scripts a bit, gives their weapons a sensible range, makes them immune to \"Lower Resistance\" and to poison, and tries to prevent situations where golems get stuck behind barricades. It also fixes an animation glitch in the Iron Golem animation - this hopefully makes iron golems a bit prettier when they attack and blow clouds.\nWith this component the flesh golem is immune to the following spells and status effects: &lt;a href=\"Web\"&gt;Web&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Entangle\"&gt;Entangle&lt;/a&gt;. Plant Growth, &lt;a href=\"Paralyze\"&gt;Paralyze&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Poison%20damage\"&gt;Poison damage&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower Resistance&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Magic\"&gt;Pierce Magic&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Shield\"&gt;Pierce Shield&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis golem now has a melee attack range reach of 2, instead of the unmodified creature's range of 1. "}
{"id": "56098", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=56098", "title": "Flesh Golem (Manual)", "text": "Flesh Golem is summoned from using the &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Manual\"&gt;Golem Manual&lt;/a&gt;. This article is about that specific creature, and not the other &lt;a href=\"Flesh%20Golem\"&gt;Flesh Golem&lt;/a&gt; versions.\nThe Golem Manual is only available in the original Throne of Bhaal game or if playing .\nGameplay.\nThis golem uses the &lt;a href=\"Clay%20Golem\"&gt;Clay Golem&lt;/a&gt; animation.\nThe golem is a controlled creature. It is best used by the player directing its movement and who/what to target.\nIf left to make decisions on its own during battle, the script it is furnished is very simplistic and may not perform to the player's liking.\nThe golem will act as a basic melee fighting creature usings its bludgeoning fists to beat on a target.\nWhen fighting an enemy in melee that is equipped with a magical weapon, the golem won't last very long, as its armor class is frankly not good, and the golem has a low hit point value.\nThe golem can be useful as a distraction, especially against magic spell casting oriented creatures, such as a mage, lich, or beholder, due to its immunities and &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;.\nThis golem can be buffed by the party to increase its effectiveness, such as with a &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Haste&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Evil%20%28wizard%29\"&gt;Protection From Evil (wizard)&lt;/a&gt; spells.\nThe golem will disappear from the map when 1 turn expires.\nA &lt;a href=\"Death%20Spell\"&gt;Death Spell&lt;/a&gt; will destroy/banish this golem, as its gender is \"summoned\".\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; makes a few revisions to this particular golem.\nThe default AI script is modified, so that if the golem is allowed by the player to do its own thing, it has a decision logic that evaluates if an enemy is protected by &lt;a href=\"Mirror%20Image\"&gt;Mirror Image&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Stoneskin\"&gt;Stoneskin&lt;/a&gt;, and then may try a different available target to pummel.\nIt also recognizes when its fists get a \"weapon ineffective\" result and will look for a different target.\nThe mod makes the golem immune to the spells &lt;a href=\"Lower%20Resistance\"&gt;Lower Resistance&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Magic\"&gt;Pierce Magic&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Pierce%20Shield\"&gt;Pierce Shield&lt;/a&gt;.\nIf the &lt;a href=\"Golem%20Construction%20for%20Spellcasters\"&gt;Golem Construction for Spellcasters&lt;/a&gt; mod is installed, the creature's sprite animation is changed to the Icewind Dale style flesh golem."}
{"id": "29302", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29302", "title": "Flesh golems", "text": ""}
{"id": "5781", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5781", "title": "Flesh to Stone", "text": "Flesh to Stone turns the flesh of, and all items carried by, the target creature to stone. \nGameplay.\nThe caster directs this spell toward a single creature in range - use the targeting cursor to designate the creature.\nWhen the spell cast is finished, a projectile speeds to the designated creature unerringly, and exposed to the &lt;a href=\"Petrified\"&gt;Petrified&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nThe creature is allowed a &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; versus Spell to resist it.\nIf the saving throw is failed, the creature is turned to stone, including all its carried gear/equipment.\nA party member affected by this spell is removed from the party and is no longer selectable.\nShould a petrified creature be subjected to any kind of damage the \"statue\" form breaks apart into chunks of stone, and is irreversibly destroyed, including not being able to remove the petrified effect nor resurrected/revived. - they are permanently dead. \nIf &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; is affected by this spell, it is game over.\nA statue creature can be cured of this petrification state using a &lt;a href=\"Stone%20to%20Flesh\"&gt;Stone to Flesh&lt;/a&gt; spell (except for the player's main character).\nThis spell can be potentially blocked with &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;.\nA &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Alteration&lt;/a&gt; will negate this spell, as will any &lt;a href=\"Spell%20protections%20type\"&gt;Spell protections type&lt;/a&gt; defensive spell with a capacity to absorb a 6 &lt;a href=\"Power%20level\"&gt;Power level&lt;/a&gt; spell effect, such as &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Turning\"&gt;Spell Turning&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a href=\"Shield%20of%20the%20Archons\"&gt;Shield of the Archons&lt;/a&gt;, and others.\nObviously, a &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Petrification\"&gt;Protection From Petrification&lt;/a&gt; spell or &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Petrification%20%28protection%20scroll%29\"&gt;scroll&lt;/a&gt; will prevent this spell from working, as will the &lt;a href=\"Avoid%20Death\"&gt;Avoid Death&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Favored%20of%20the%20Spirits\"&gt;Favored of the Spirits&lt;/a&gt; spell/abilities.\nEquipment items carried by a destroyed statue that are flagged as \"critical\" will be placed on the ground, but all other items are destroyed.\nNeutral creatures in the vicinity of someone petrified by this spell will probably become hostile.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition Wizard spell \"Stone to Flesh\" has a reversable ability to cause a \"Flesh to Stone\" spell function - however the Pen and Paper game doesn't list the Wizard spell Flesh to Stone separately as they do in the BG game.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, revising its effects, saving throw and description. See below:\nFlesh to Stone\nLevel: 6\nSchool: Alteration\nRange: Long\nDuration: Special\nCasting Time: 6\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: Special\nFlesh to Stone is a powerful magic that permanently turns the flesh of the creature affected into stone. When struck by this spell the target is slowed for 3 rounds as its flesh begins to harden. The following round the subject of the spell must save vs. petrification at -4 or be turned into a statue. A dispel magic spell cannot restore the victim\u2019s natural form, but some powerful spells, such as Stone to Flesh or Freedom, can. This spell has no effect on undead, constructs, or incorporeal creatures."}
