{"id": "47167", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=47167", "title": "Free Action (scroll)", "text": ""}
{"id": "5101", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5101", "title": "Free Action (spell)", "text": "Free Action is a 4th level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt; mainly available to the &lt;a href=\"cleric\"&gt;cleric&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"paladin\"&gt;paladin&lt;/a&gt; classes. See the InfoBox for classes that can cast it from a scroll.\nGameplay.\nThe caster applies this spell to self or one creature - the spell has a \"touch\" range.\nWhen the spell is applied, the recipient will show a 3d graphic rendered over their sprite, and for the duration of the spell will have a pulsing color glow effect - additionally, a player character will also display an icon (No. 10) titled \"Free Action\" on their portrait while the spell is active. \nA sound effect is audibled upon casting the spell, and another when the spell expires. \nThe following immunities are provided by the spell:\nOther effects.\nTo clarify, this spell not only offers protection from a number of free movement hindering effects, but it also prevents other effects that change movement, such as the &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;Haste effect&lt;/a&gt;, no matter how it is applied. \nFor example, a character that is already under the boosted speed effects of an &lt;a href=\"Oil%20of%20Speed\"&gt;Oil of Speed&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Haste&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a href=\"Improved%20Haste\"&gt;Improved Haste&lt;/a&gt; will still retain those benefits even if a Free Action spell is cast upon them, but if the Free Action spell is active on a character before those same haste boosting effects are applied, they will fail.\nThe Free Action spell doesn't affect an &lt;a href=\"Offensive%20Spin\"&gt;Offensive Spin&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Whirlwind%20Attack\"&gt;Whirlwind Attack&lt;/a&gt;.\nAdditionally, the spell's &lt;a href=\"Free%20Action%20%28status%20effect%29\"&gt;Free Action (status effect)&lt;/a&gt; ensures that a creature's movement rate/modifier is set back to its base value - this means that movement boosting items won't provide their extra bonus, such as &lt;a href=\"The%20Paws%20of%20the%20Cheetah\"&gt;The Paws of the Cheetah&lt;/a&gt; - this won't affect innate movement bonuses available through experience levels or character class which boost movement, such as the &lt;a href=\"Barbarian\"&gt;Barbarian&lt;/a&gt; or the &lt;a href=\"Monk\"&gt;Monk&lt;/a&gt; receive.\nThe Free Action spell may be used as a cure to a number of status effects afflicted on a creature - so in that regard, it has better utility than a &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Freedom\"&gt;Potion of Freedom&lt;/a&gt;, which can prevent status effects and spells, but can't be imbibed by a character who is already afflicted (a &lt;a href=\"Paralyze\"&gt;paralyzed&lt;/a&gt; person can't drink a potion).\nThe Free Action spell can be removed by various &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effects and a &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt; spell.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this Divine spell, revising its duration, effects, and description. See below:\nFree Action\nLevel: 4\nSchool: Abjuration\nSphere: Charm\nRange: Touch\nDuration: 1 turn/level\nCasting Time: 5\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: None\nWhile under the effects of this spell, the recipient becomes immune to everything, magical or otherwise, that limits his mobility in any way. This includes, but is not limited to, Entangle, Grease, Web, Hold, Slow, and Stun. This effect will last for the duration of the spell or until dispelled."}
{"id": "23315", "revid": "46775035", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=23315", "title": "Free Action (status effect)", "text": "The Free action &lt;a href=\"Status%20Effects\"&gt;effect&lt;/a&gt; is used by the game in a bundle, together with many other effects, to build a somewhat consistent feature also called Free Action. This article first describes the effect as part of a series on status effects, and goes on to detail the bundle itself in &lt;a href=\"%23Free%20Action%20bundle\"&gt;its own section&lt;/a&gt;, down the page.\nWhen game descriptions refer to \"Free Action\", they never talk about the single Free action effect, always the bundle of many effects.\nMechanics.\nNever used alone, always with other effects, the Free action effect is on its own a cure of sorts: When applied to a creature, it clears some negative arrangements of the \"Movement rate bonus\" effect, potentially restoring its movement speed to normal if it had been lowered.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Enhanced%20Edition\"&gt;Enhanced Edition&lt;/a&gt;s, there is virtually no arrangement where the Free action effect \"alone\" would be useful, as the target is either affected by worse movement-related ailments at the same time, or the \"Movement rate bonus\" inflicted is no longer using one of the negative arrangements cleared by the Free action effect.\nIn the &lt;a href=\"original%20edition\"&gt;original edition&lt;/a&gt;s, it alone would be enough to restore movement of a creature affected by &lt;a href=\"Grease\"&gt;Grease&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Entangle\"&gt;Entangle&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Plant%20Growth\"&gt;Plant Growth&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Defensive%20Spin\"&gt;Defensive Spin&lt;/a&gt; and wild surges #&lt;a href=\"Wild%20Surge%2311\"&gt;11&lt;/a&gt; &amp; &lt;a href=\"Wild%20Surge%2369\"&gt;69&lt;/a&gt; \"Entangle(d)\", as well as the attacks of &lt;a href=\"Nyalee\"&gt;Nyalee&lt;/a&gt; and her &lt;a href=\"Shambling%20Mound%20%28Forest%20of%20Mir%29\"&gt;Shambling Mound&lt;/a&gt;s.\nFree Action bundle.\nThough not perfectly consistent from spell to item, this bundle of many effects labeled \"Free Action\" by the game can be expected to first cure any pre-existing &lt;a href=\"Stun\"&gt;Stun&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Paralyze\"&gt;Paralyze&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Held\"&gt;Hold creature&lt;/a&gt; effect, as well as sluggishness born from causes other than the &lt;a href=\"Slow%20effect\"&gt;Slow&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Disease\"&gt;Disease&lt;/a&gt; effects. Then, for as long as it is active, it can be expected to grant immunity to any new application of &lt;a href=\"Haste%20effect\"&gt;Haste&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Slow%20effect\"&gt;Slow&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Webbed\"&gt;Web&lt;/a&gt;, Hold creature and Paralyze effects, as well as positive and negative alterations of speed besides the slowing type of &lt;a href=\"Disease\"&gt;Disease&lt;/a&gt; effect. In some game variants it may grant immunity to the Stun effect as well.\nParty members should expect to receive an \u00a0icon on their portrait when game descriptions say they will be affected by \"Free Action\".\nIt is possible to benefit from both haste and free action if the Haste effect is applied \"before\" the Free Action bundle of effects, because the bundle does not cure a pre-existing haste on arrival, it only prevents it from being applied for as long as the bundle's immunities are active.\u00a0For example, a mage could cast &lt;a href=\"Haste\"&gt;Haste&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0first on a fighter, who would then and only then equip &lt;a href=\"Edventar%27s%20Gift\"&gt;Edventar's Gift&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0to benefit from both effects.\u00a0That wouldn't work if the fighter wore the ring from the start.\nMod content.\nThe &lt;a href=\"klatu%20Tweaks%20and%20Fixes\"&gt;klatu Tweaks and Fixes&lt;/a&gt; makes the Free Action feature consistent across the various items and spells, and makes sure hasting is always possible."}
{"id": "12047", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12047", "title": "Free Frennedan from his cell", "text": "Free Frennedan from his cell is an unmarked minor quest in of .\nWalkthrough.\nAfter reaching the second level of Irenicus' &lt;a href=\"Irenicus%27s%20Dungeon%202nd%20Floor\"&gt;dungeon&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; will find a unlocked door to a room with an adjoining glass-walled room from which a 'commoner' named Frennedan pleads for his freedom. The &lt;a href=\"Key%20to%20Frennedan%27s%20Room\"&gt;key&lt;/a&gt; to the door of this second room can be found in a trapped chest in the first room.\nFrennedan is actually a &lt;a href=\"doppelganger\"&gt;doppelganger&lt;/a&gt; in disguise. If he is released, he immediately turns on the party when next they are in combat or after a few minutes have passed. Upon opening his cell, however, you also have the option to attack him. Regardless of how he becomes hostile, he always reverts to his natural form when he does.\nIf you refuse to free him, he shapeshifts into a child in an ill-conceived attempt to make his plight seem more desperate.\nIt is recommended to have every member of the party engage Frennedan with ranged weapons till he reaches the party, as he is able to regularly hit individuals with maximum &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;Armor Class&lt;/a&gt; available at the time"}
{"id": "5973", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5973", "title": "Free Haer'Dalis from Imprisonment by Mekrath", "text": "Free Haer'Dalis from Imprisonment by Mekrath is a companion quest in the campaign. it can be started in the &lt;a href=\"Five%20Flagons%20Theatre\"&gt;basement&lt;/a&gt; of the &lt;a href=\"Five%20Flagons%20Inn\"&gt;Five Flagons Inn&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Bridge%20District\"&gt;Bridge District&lt;/a&gt; and allows recruiting the &lt;a href=\"Blade\"&gt;bard&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Haer%27Dalis\"&gt;Haer'Dalis&lt;/a&gt;.\nAquisition.\nThis quest is followed by &lt;a href=\"Rescue%20Raelis%20and%20Haer%27Dalis%20from%20the%20planar%20prison\"&gt;Rescue Raelis and Haer'Dalis from the planar prison&lt;/a&gt; to ensure his stay in the party. The latter quest opens up the &lt;a href=\"Running%20the%20Five%20Flagons%20Playhouse\"&gt;bard's stronghold&lt;/a&gt; quest."}
{"id": "6079", "revid": "3983911", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=6079", "title": "Free Haer'Dalis from Inprisonment by Mekrath", "text": ""}
{"id": "5958", "revid": "283830", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5958", "title": "Free Hendak and the slaves", "text": "Free Hendak and the Slaves is a side-quest. It can be started in the &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet\"&gt;Copper Coronet&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Athkatla%20Slums\"&gt;Athkatla Slums&lt;/a&gt;.\nAquisition.\nIn order to get this quest, the player must first resolve parts of the &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20activities%20in%20the%20Copper%20Coronet%27s%20rooms\"&gt;Investigate activities in the Copper Coronet's rooms&lt;/a&gt; questline. \nIn order to get the \"Free Hendak and slave quest\", the party must speak with &lt;a href=\"Hendak\"&gt;Hendak&lt;/a&gt; and agree to liberate him, and the other slaves locked up in the Copper Coronet. If the player agrees to help, the player's journal will register the quest, as follows:\nWalkthrough and gameplay.\nPart 1: The Copper Coronet slaves.\nIn the rear and restricted areas of the Copper Coronet Hendak can be found. Locked in a cell with another slave gladiator. Several children are also locked up back here.\nYou will be warned by a &lt;a href=\"Copper%20Coronet%20Guard\"&gt;guard&lt;/a&gt; to leave this area immediately, and he means it. The only option to prevent the guards from turning hostile is to agree to leave (if you agreed to leave then attempt to speak to &lt;a href=\"Hendak\"&gt;Hendak&lt;/a&gt;, this will turn them hostile anyway). After defeating the guards, Hendak, the ex-gladiator slave, will initiate dialogue (if a party member is close enough to the cell door) and then urge you to free him and the other slaves. If you agree, the quest registers in the Journal. If you don't agree a journal entry will register as follows:\nFrom this point, you have the option of reporting Hendak's escape plan back to &lt;a href=\"Lehtinan\"&gt;Lehtinan&lt;/a&gt;, who will give you the &lt;a href=\"Beastmaster%20Key\"&gt;Beastmaster Key&lt;/a&gt; and ask you to kill Hendak instead (&lt;a href=\"Aerie\"&gt;Aerie&lt;/a&gt;'ll turn hostile but &lt;a href=\"Keldorn%20Firecam\"&gt;Keldorn&lt;/a&gt; will not, surprise). If you report it, but decline to take care of killing Hendak, then his guards will do it. Hendak will be killed (you don't see this), and the \"Free Hendak and the slaves\" quest won't occur and is shuttered for good.&lt;br&gt;\nAssuming that at some point the player decides to speak with and agree to help Hendak then get the key from the &lt;a href=\"Beastmaster\"&gt;Beastmaster&lt;/a&gt; and liberate all the slaves in the back rooms.\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Quest%20Pack\"&gt;Quest Pack&lt;/a&gt; Mod will add a \"Further Slaver Involvement\" component. This component allows additional options in dealing with the slavers around the city:"}
