{"id": "24725", "revid": "31124876", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=24725", "title": "Dilos", "text": "Dilos is a &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist\"&gt;Flaming Fist&lt;/a&gt; mercenary who is found on the ground floor in the &lt;a href=\"Flaming%20Fist%20Headquarters\"&gt;Flaming Fist Headquarters&lt;/a&gt;. He will approach the party if any member of the party is caught snooping around the headquarters. After this first conversation, he has nothing else to say. During &lt;a href=\"Chapter%207\"&gt;Chapter 7&lt;/a&gt;, he will recognise the party as the ones wanted for murder and attack them."}
{"id": "5030", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5030", "title": "Dimension Door", "text": "Dimension Door teleports the casters to any location they can see.\nThis spell is only available in classic versions of , , &amp; . Cheats must be used to get it in the Enhanced Edition versions.\nThere is no scroll for this spell in the Enhanced Edition.\nBugs.\nThe spell, and similar spells like SPIN140.spl used by original game Phase Spiders can cause game crashes in the Enhanced Edition, and the spell can also be an issue if used at certain maps which can break sequences and plot triggers. This spell was removed from the game. Jumping, teleporting and blinking can be done in different ways with different spells in the EE versions, for the AI's use, but not the player. Modded content has reintroduced the teleport function for players, with some changes.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has added a new level 1 Wizard spell to fulfill the Dimension Door role in the game. See below for description:\nDimension Jump\nLevel: 1\nSchool: Conjuration\nRange: Personal\nDuration: Instant\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: Caster\nSaving Throw: None\nThis spell transports the caster to any place within sight. When the spell is cast, a dimensional portal opens up in front of the caster, which he immediately steps through. Upon passing through the portal, the caster finds himself at his chosen destination. The caster always arrives at exactly the spot desired, and the dimensional door doesn\u2019t allow anyone or anything else to pass through. Spells about to be cast upon the wizard will fail, and missiles about to hit him will instead hit thin air."}
{"id": "27409", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=27409", "title": "Dimension door", "text": ""}
{"id": "22480", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=22480", "title": "Dings", "text": "Dings is a cat given to &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; by &lt;a href=\"Barad%20Ding\"&gt;Barad Ding&lt;/a&gt; after &lt;a href=\"Barad%20Ding%27s%20eight%20cats\"&gt;delivering the eight cats&lt;/a&gt; safely back to him, if s/he is a &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; (including dual or multi-class mages) or &lt;a href=\"sorcerer\"&gt;sorcerer&lt;/a&gt;.\nGameplay.\nPerhaps the term Gameplay is being too generous for this cat, Dings. There is no play going to happen. Dings is not a creature file, but an item file, and will be in the backpack inventory.\nPerhaps the purpose of this quirky item is to stimulate the protagonist to go back and try and return this cat to Barad. There are quite a few dialogue lines available for this subject.\nMaybe when the PC agreed to take this cat while imagining of all the great things to do with it, like a familiar. Perhaps the cat could scout for the party, or steal small items? Alas, it's a Tabby cat that just sleeps mostly. And poops in the backpack.\nIf you remove the cat from the backpack, you can transfer it to other party members. You can also place it on the ground, and it appears not as a cat, but a small bag. You could even just place it in a random container if you like. It has no value so can't be sold - because according to the game it is a \"critical item\". The term critical seems to be subjective here."}
{"id": "9057", "revid": "47673695", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=9057", "title": "Dinguer the Mad", "text": "Dinguer the Mad is the spell in \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Black%20Pits\"&gt;The Black Pits&lt;/a&gt;\".\nHe is probably mad and plotting his revenge against &lt;a href=\"Baeloth%20Barrityl\"&gt;Baeloth&lt;/a&gt;.\nDinguer the Mad (store).\nDinguer offers various categories of , with the whole palette of protection scrolls, unlimited supply of &lt;a href=\"Stone%20to%20Flesh%20Scroll\"&gt;Stone to Flesh&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Restoration\"&gt;Greater Restoration&lt;/a&gt;, and almost all available &lt;a href=\"wizard%20spells\"&gt;wizard spells&lt;/a&gt; up to level five.\nUnlike all the other in \"&lt;a href=\"The%20Black%20Pits\"&gt;The Black Pits&lt;/a&gt;\", he sells what he sells from the beginning, and does not improve or refill his stock as the &lt;a href=\"party\"&gt;party&lt;/a&gt; progresses throughout the various \"tiers\" of the arena fights. Instead, scrolls of spell level five can be found right at the start. This comes with a slightly increased cost: Dinguer sells at 160% of an &lt;a href=\"item\"&gt;item&lt;/a&gt;'s base value, where the other merchants demand 15% less. As the others, however, he buys far more than only scrolls for 30% item value at a &lt;a href=\"depreciation%20rate\"&gt;depreciation rate&lt;/a&gt; of 5. Prices might be further modified through high &lt;a href=\"charisma\"&gt;charisma&lt;/a&gt; or an other-than-average &lt;a href=\"reputation\"&gt;reputation&lt;/a&gt;.\nIt is not possible to steal from him personally or his wares."}
{"id": "11468", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11468", "title": "Dirbert", "text": "Dirbert' is barely more than a child but, despite his youth, ignorance and inexperience, he is quite eager to embark on a career as an adventurer with his comrades, &lt;a href=\"Neler\"&gt;Neler&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Valsben\"&gt;Valsben&lt;/a&gt;. He contracts &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and their party to get them started on their 'path to glory.' He can be found waiting just north of &lt;a href=\"Jermien%27s%20Home\"&gt;Jermien's Home&lt;/a&gt;.\nSide quests.\n&lt;a href=\"Idle%20hands%20in%20Imnesvale\"&gt;Idle hands in Imnesvale&lt;/a&gt;.\nDirbert and his friends are too eager - and far too stupid - to become adventurers, though this fact is lost on them. They insist that someone should buy them &lt;a href=\"Bastard%20Sword\"&gt;bastard swords&lt;/a&gt; and a round of &lt;a href=\"De%27Tranion%27s%20Baalor%20Ale\"&gt;De'Tranion's Baalor Ale&lt;/a&gt;. Depending on the option chosen, several more side quests can become available as a result, if all of the Imnesvale would-be adventurers are not slain."}
{"id": "5002", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5002", "title": "Dire Charm", "text": "Dire Charm will let the caster gain control of the victim.\nGameplay.\nThe caster directs this spell towards a single target creature in range.\nWhen the spell is finished a magical projectile flies to the target creature and exposes it to the &lt;a href=\"Charmed\"&gt;Charmed&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nThe target (if classified as a \"person\") must make a &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;Saving throw&lt;/a&gt; versus spells or will be charmed for spell's duration.\nIf charmed, the person's allegiance changes to an Ally - and are considered a \"party member\" in terms of being friendly to the party.\nThis spell applies Charm Type 3 to the person - \"Dire charmed (Target hostile after effect ends)\".\nIf a player character is affected by this spell, they'll display an icon (No. 1) titled \"Dire Charm\", and when the spell expires a sound effect will audible.\nIn the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Original&lt;/a&gt; and editions of BG1 only, many commoners and enemies have &lt;a href=\"Charmed\"&gt;hidden dialogues&lt;/a&gt; spoken only under charm. You may manually initiate dialogue with them by using the codice_1 button. These hidden dialogues are usually but simple and amusing quotes, but sometimes they do reveal more substantial clues.\nAttacking or damaging actions towards the charmed person ends the charmed state.\nAt least in &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20II\"&gt;Baldur's Gate II&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Nymph%20Cloak\"&gt;Nymph Cloak&lt;/a&gt; or the &lt;a href=\"Ring%20of%20Human%20Influence\"&gt;Ring of Human Influence&lt;/a&gt; can be used instead of this spell to apply a Charm Type 0 - \"Charmed (Target neutral after effect ends)\". \nThis spell can be blocked by &lt;a href=\"Magic%20resistance\"&gt;Magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;, or any spell protection, such as &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Spell%20Deflection\"&gt;Minor Spell Deflection&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Minor%20Globe%20of%20Invulnerability\"&gt;Minor Globe of Invulnerability&lt;/a&gt;.\nA &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity: Enchantment&lt;/a&gt; will nullify this spell.\nNote that &lt;a href=\"Elf\"&gt;Elf&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Half-elf\"&gt;Half-elf&lt;/a&gt; creatures are 90% and 35% resistant respectively to this spell.\nThe spell can be removed with any &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effect.\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons &amp; Dragons 2nd Edition \"Dire Charm\" Wizard spell makes the victim attack anyone but the caster in a berserk state. See the External links for further information. \nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, revising its duration. See below for description:\nDire Charm\nLevel: 3\nSchool: Enchantment\nRange: Long\nDuration: 1 turn\nCasting Time: 3\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: Spell negates\nThis spell works in the exact same manner as Charm Person, with two differences: the saving throw has no bonus, and the enchantment has a longer duration. Dire Charm affects any single person it is cast upon. The term person includes any bipedal human, demihuman, or humanoid of man-size or smaller, such as dwarves, elves, gnolls, gnomes, half-elves, halflings, half-orcs, hobgoblins, humans, kobolds, and others. Thus, a 10th-level fighter could be charmed, but an ogre could not. If the recipient fails his saving throw, he regards the caster as a trusted friend and ally to be heeded and protected. The caster may give him orders, and the charmed creature will carry them out as quickly as possible.\nIf the caster harms, or attempts to harm, the charmed creature by some overt action, or if a Dispel Magic spell is successfully cast upon the charmed creature, the charm spell is broken. If two or more charm effects simultaneously affect a creature, the most recent charm takes precedence."}
{"id": "11184", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11184", "title": "Dire Wolf", "text": "Dire Wolves are somewhat common enemies found in woodland areas of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast\"&gt;Sword Coast&lt;/a&gt;.\nDescription.\nThey are more dangerous than ordinary &lt;a href=\"Wolf\"&gt;wolves&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"worg\"&gt;worg&lt;/a&gt;s but not as dangerous as &lt;a href=\"Dread%20Wolf\"&gt;dread wolves.&lt;/a&gt; They are sometimes found in groups, but they are more likely to travel alone than ordinary wolves. They have no special abilities, but can be dangerous to low-level parties.\nGameplay.\nIn melee, their attack is considered a +1 magical and enchanted weapon that deals 1d8 &lt;a href=\"Piercing%20damage\"&gt;piercing&lt;/a&gt; damage, (adjusted for Strength bonus in ).\nSummons.\nDire Wolves can be summoned by the Priest spell &lt;a href=\"Animal%20Summoning%20I\"&gt;Animal Summoning I&lt;/a&gt;. The Wizard spell &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20III\"&gt;Monster Summoning III&lt;/a&gt; in \"Baldur's Gate\" or &lt;a href=\"Monster%20Summoning%20II\"&gt;Monster Summoning II&lt;/a&gt; in \"Shadows of Amn\" can also be used. Summoned versions are virtually identical."}
