{"id": "3388", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=3388", "title": "Discipliner", "text": "The Discipliner is an item which appears in \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\", \"\", and the Enhanced Edition versions.\nGameplay.\nOtherwise known as the Ring of Folly, this item is a cursed ring made to humiliate the most careless, skilled, and egotistical students of arcane magic. They see this as a 'gift' instead of punishment of a disapproving teacher. After this experience, the teacher hopes this student becomes humbler and more careful.\nThe wearer of the ring is afflicted with a &lt;a href=\"Feeblemindedness\"&gt;Feeblemindedness&lt;/a&gt; effect, and intelligence and wisdom are set to 3. If the wearer isn't protected against these effects, then it can't be resisted.\nAs the item is flagged with a \"cursed\" field, a &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Curse\"&gt;Remove Curse&lt;/a&gt; effect is required in order to take off the ring from the afflicted creature. Then, after that, the &lt;a href=\"Feeblemindedness\"&gt;Feeblemindedness&lt;/a&gt; must be cured as well - in order to be able to manipulate the party members &lt;a href=\"Inventory\"&gt;Inventory&lt;/a&gt;.\nWearing the ring during a solo game effectively causes a \"game over\", as the effect is permanent, and the character is held in place with no means of curing themselves."}
{"id": "37920", "revid": "49135869", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=37920", "title": "Disease", "text": "Disease is a status effect that causes a single ailment from the following list:\nWhich ailment the victim receives is entirely decided by who or what causes the disease. For example, the &lt;a href=\"Contagion\"&gt;Contagion&lt;/a&gt; spell inflicts four different Disease effects, three affecting base stats and one causing slow.\nOther ailments exist, but they are not used in the unmodded game. \nDiseases that are not a Disease effect.\nThe Disease portrait icon is sometimes used for afflictions that are not actually a Disease effect proper. One example of this is the &lt;a href=\"Ghast\"&gt;Ghast&lt;/a&gt;, whose attack may inflict a cumulative +2 &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; penalty along with a Disease portrait icon, lasting for 200 seconds. Since no Disease effect is involved whatsoever, immunity to it will not help.\nIn , &lt;a href=\"Cure%20Disease\"&gt;Cure Disease&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Neutralize%20Poison\"&gt;Neutralize Poison&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Restoration\"&gt;Greater Restoration&lt;/a&gt; should however be able to cure this type of illness in most cases. Failing that, &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; should often work as a cure of sorts."}
{"id": "21073", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=21073", "title": "Diseased Gibberling", "text": "A Diseased Gibberling is a variant of the &lt;a href=\"Gibberling\"&gt;Gibberling&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe first impression of gibberlings is of a writhing mass of fur and flesh.\nDespite the name, diseased gibberlings do not transmit any diseases with their attacks."}
{"id": "51802", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=51802", "title": "Diseased Rat", "text": "Diseased Rat is a hostile animal. They are spawned by script from various game enemy creatures, similar to a summoned creature, but actually just spawned. They are spawned in groups of 10-12.\nGameplay.\nThese small creatures can only attack with weak &lt;a href=\"Piercing%20damage\"&gt;Piercing damage&lt;/a&gt; bites, twice per round. \nIf a bite hits, then a &lt;a href=\"Disease\"&gt;Disease&lt;/a&gt; effect is applied inflicting damage each second, for six consecutive seconds. The damage is 1% (minimum of 1 damage) of the targets current Hit points. \nAs this is a disease effect, it is a &lt;a href=\"Poison%20damage\"&gt;Poison damage&lt;/a&gt; applied. There is no saving throw.\nUnlike ordinary &lt;a href=\"Rat\"&gt;Rat&lt;/a&gt; brethren, these foul rodents are evil and malign.\nThey spawn by certain boss enemies, such as a few &lt;a href=\"Vampire\"&gt;Vampire&lt;/a&gt; creatures, or the Shaman &lt;a href=\"Nilthiri\"&gt;Nilthiri&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe rats serve as a distraction, clog up the battlefield to occlude free movement, and buy time for the spawning originator."}
