{"id": "5117", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=5117", "title": "Doom", "text": "Doom is a 1st level &lt;a href=\"priest%20spell\"&gt;priest spell&lt;/a&gt;. It impairs a target, reducing their &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"saving%20throw\"&gt;saving throw&lt;/a&gt;s.\nGameplay.\nCasting Doom upon a neutral creature will make them hostile.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this divine spell, revising its effects, casting time, school, and description. See below:\nDoom\nLevel: 1\nSchool: Enchantment\nSphere: Charm\nRange: Long\nDuration: 1 turn\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: 1 creature\nSaving Throw: Spell negates\nThis spell causes a feeling of doom to overwhelm the target. For the duration of the spell, the target receives a -2 penalty to attack rolls, damage rolls, and saving throws, unless a save vs. spell is made. The creature has a saving throw penalty of -1 (to save against this spell) for every two extra levels of the caster, to a maximum of -4 at 9th level. Multiple castings of this spell are not cumulative."}
{"id": "24339", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=24339", "title": "Doom Guard", "text": "Doom Guards are , created from empty suits of animated by magic rituals. They are only encountered in .\nGameplay.\nThough immune to &lt;a href=\"missile%20damage\"&gt;missile damage&lt;/a&gt;, the on-hit effect from magical such as the &lt;a href=\"Acid%20Arrow\"&gt;Acid Arrow&lt;/a&gt; does affect them and can bring them down quickly.\nBugs.\n In the original &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;, the weapon's additional 1d8 damage is slashing, not fire.\nTrivia.\nDoom guards aren't of any &lt;a href=\"race\"&gt;race&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"class\"&gt;class&lt;/a&gt; in the original \"Baldur's Gate\". Although &lt;a href=\"Flesh%20Golem\"&gt;Flesh Golem&lt;/a&gt;s are encountered in the game, true &lt;a href=\"golems\"&gt;golems&lt;/a&gt; were only introduced with its successor, '. The ' uses these resources and gives Doom guards a true &lt;a href=\"construct\"&gt;construct&lt;/a&gt;-like status, while simultaneously changing their gender from to &lt;a href=\"male\"&gt;male&lt;/a&gt; \u2013 an exception amongst golems, which tend to have the former one.\nSee also.\n&lt;a href=\"Dwarven%20Doom%20Guard\"&gt;Dwarven Doom Guard&lt;/a&gt;\nGallery.\nA Doom Guard in different strike poses"}
{"id": "4973", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=4973", "title": "Doomplate", "text": "Doomplate +3 is a piece enchanted plate mail +3. It provides an armor class of 0 and +3 protection against slashing weapons, as any normal set of &lt;a href=\"Plate%20Mail\"&gt;plate mail&lt;/a&gt;. It has a weight of 27 lbs. Despite the name and the in-game description which might suggest the armor is cursed, this is not the case. This item appears in . It's gained as a reward from the genie in the Asylum Gauntlet, after finding the three gems and defeating the monsters which come out of the portal."}
{"id": "20312", "revid": "978785", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20312", "title": "Doomplate +3", "text": ""}
{"id": "7657", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=7657", "title": "Doomsayer", "text": "The Doomsayer is the guardian of an ancient temple of &lt;a href=\"Talos\"&gt;Kozah&lt;/a&gt; in the &lt;a href=\"Archaeological%20Site\"&gt;Archaeological Site&lt;/a&gt; south of the &lt;a href=\"Lighthouse\"&gt;Lighthouse&lt;/a&gt;. This temple is being excavated by &lt;a href=\"Charleston%20Nib\"&gt;Charleston Nib&lt;/a&gt;. If the &lt;a href=\"Idol\"&gt;Idol of Kozah&lt;/a&gt; is taken out of the temple, the Doomsayer will appear and attack, after a brief dialogue.\nThe Doomsayer targets the nearest party member with melee attacks, and is quite powerful. Even at level 6, the party member being attacked will need extensive healing and other support (&lt;a href=\"Bless\"&gt;Bless&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Evil\"&gt;Protection From Evil&lt;/a&gt;, etc.) to survive the encounter. Like all non-magic resistant melee attackers, it is easily trivialized with the first level spell &lt;a href=\"Grease\"&gt;Grease&lt;/a&gt;.\nThe Doomsayer can only be damaged by enchanted weapons and ammunition, and is immune to electrical damage.\nThe rewards offered by fighting the Doomsayer are minimal, and ultimately it is not recommended.\nEquipment.\nThe Doomsayer appears as a &lt;a href=\"human\"&gt;human&lt;/a&gt; male &lt;a href=\"fighter\"&gt;fighter&lt;/a&gt; and comes equipped with a &lt;a href=\"Helmet%23Plumed%20Crest%20Helmet\"&gt;plumed crest helmet&lt;/a&gt; (immunity to critical hits) and &lt;a href=\"Plate%20Mail\"&gt;Plate Mail&lt;/a&gt;; the latter, however, doesn't have any effects on his &lt;a href=\"Armor%20Class\"&gt;armor class&lt;/a&gt;, as he has a natural AC of -2 that is further lowered by 3 through his &lt;a href=\"dexterity\"&gt;dexterity&lt;/a&gt;. He wields a flame blade, similar to the weapon created by the &lt;a href=\"Flame%20Blade\"&gt;spell&lt;/a&gt;, that in the classic &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; deals 1d4 +4 fire damage and gives a -4 bonus to the Doomsayer's already low &lt;a href=\"THAC0\"&gt;THAC0&lt;/a&gt; of 8.\nIn addition he wears two . One of these grants him immunity to a number of &lt;a href=\"Status%20Effects\"&gt;status effects&lt;/a&gt;: berserk, charm, confusion, fatigue, panic, paralyze, petrification, poison, slay and sleep. The other one creates a field of &lt;a href=\"blur\"&gt;blur&lt;/a&gt; that lowers his already very low armor class by an additional -3 bonus, to an overall value of -8, and adds a -1 bonus to all of his &lt;a href=\"saving%20throw\"&gt;saving throw&lt;/a&gt;s.\nHe doesn't drop any items upon death.\nTactics.\nIn the original \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\", &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; will make all the difference when fighting the Doomsayer: it dispels his &lt;a href=\"Blur\"&gt;Blur&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Flame%20Blade\"&gt;Flame Blade&lt;/a&gt;. With fists alone, the Doomsayer's damage is minimized and he is never able to kill, as fists only knock someone out. In the \"\", however, dispelling magic has no effect at all on these built-in abilities.\nFire, ice, acid and magic damage spells will work. Lightning will heal him, as he has over 100% lightning resistance. &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Frost\"&gt;Wands of Frost&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Magic%20Missiles\"&gt;Magic Missiles&lt;/a&gt; work. &lt;a href=\"Wand%20of%20Paralyzation\"&gt;Wand of Paralyzation&lt;/a&gt; works even better. Also, in case Dispel Magic misfires, have &lt;a href=\"Oil%20of%20Speed\"&gt;Oil of Speed&lt;/a&gt; prepped for one of your main fighters armed with powerful weapons. Note also that ranged weapons can be helpful to halt the Doomsayer just enough to maximize the effect of Web.\nWhile he's immune to the damage of missiles, he's not to their magical component, so &lt;a href=\"Acid%20Arrow\"&gt;Acid Arrow&lt;/a&gt;s and similar will partially work.\nGrease + Magic Missile.\nNot even cheese, just a good grasp of the magic system - Grease is a first level spell with a good duration that slows movement to a crawl even on a successful saving throw, completely neutering the Doomsayer's ability to deal its ferocious melee damage. So incapacitated, the Doomsayer can be safely dealt with at range. The most effective means to do so by is Magic Missile; the projectiles always hit (ignoring its impressive AC) and completely bypass its elemental based resistances. The Doomsayer requires around twenty-four missiles to reliably destroy (eight castings of the fifth level version suffices) and can easily be soloed by a fifth level mage with the &lt;a href=\"Evermemory\"&gt;Ring of Wizardry.&lt;/a&gt;\nFleeing.\nTo disengage, you'll need a distraction, and the best one is probably summoning creatures to keep him busy. &lt;a href=\"Web\"&gt;Web&lt;/a&gt; will work well enough, though he has high saving throws (at least whilst blurred) and won't give up the chase despite being out of sight. You'd probably have to flee the zone and return to disengage combat.\nExploits.\nThe easiest way of killing Doomsayer is to lure him towards &lt;a href=\"Brage\"&gt;Brage&lt;/a&gt;. Thanks to his &lt;a href=\"Two-handed%20Sword%2C%20Cursed%20Berserking\"&gt;cursed sword&lt;/a&gt;, the captain will turn &lt;a href=\"berserk\"&gt;berserk&lt;/a&gt; in the presence of an enemy and will go after the apparition. At this point it's best to quaff a &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Invisibility\"&gt;Potion of Invisibility&lt;/a&gt; or to &lt;a href=\"Stealth\"&gt;hide in shadows&lt;/a&gt; (the cart remains can be used to break line of sight), but simply running in circles should also work. Brage attacks only once per round and needs a good roll to hit Doomsayer, but his every hit deals very respectable damage.\nDialogue.\n\"IthNal cOR dan osa KOZAH! Rrrackne dall'a osa KOZAH!\""}
{"id": "11738", "revid": "47377093", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=11738", "title": "Doppelganger", "text": "\"Moved ne'er by rage and ne'er by anger,\"&lt;br&gt;\n\"Cold is the trait'rous doppelganger.\"&lt;br&gt;\n\u2014 Durlag Trollkiller\nDoppelgangers are insidious shapeshifters that often use their abilities to infiltrate powerful groups or organizations for various purposes. A stronger version, the &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Doppelganger\"&gt;Greater Doppelganger&lt;/a&gt;, is also capable of casting spells.\nIn &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt; they have been used by the &lt;a href=\"Iron%20Throne\"&gt;Iron Throne&lt;/a&gt; (especially &lt;a href=\"Sarevok%20Anchev\"&gt;Sarevok&lt;/a&gt;) to infiltrate and undermine the &lt;a href=\"Seven%20Suns%20Trading%20Coster\"&gt;Seven Suns Trading Coster&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href=\"Merchants%27%20League\"&gt;Merchants' League&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Candlekeep\"&gt;Candlekeep&lt;/a&gt; in order to increase the Throne's own profits and control of the region.\nThey are also found lurking in and around &lt;a href=\"Durlag%27s%20Tower\"&gt;Durlag's Tower&lt;/a&gt;.\nSide quests.\n&lt;a href=\"Investigating%20the%20Merchants%27%20League%20Estate\"&gt;Investigating the Merchants' League Estate&lt;/a&gt;.\n&lt;a href=\"Aldeth%20Sashenstar\"&gt;Aldeth Sashenstar&lt;/a&gt; (or &lt;a href=\"Dabron%20Sashenstar\"&gt;his brother&lt;/a&gt;) is convinced that something very strange is going on in the &lt;a href=\"Merchants%27%20League\"&gt;Merchants' League&lt;/a&gt;, and he asks &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; and their party for help."}
