{"id": "42199", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=42199", "title": "Blind Albino Wyrmling", "text": "The Blind Albino Wyrmlings are a pack of young metallic &lt;a href=\"wyvern\"&gt;wyvern&lt;/a&gt;s originally born to a mother named &lt;a href=\"Halatathlaer\"&gt;Halatathlaer&lt;/a&gt;. When she was killed during the last Dragonspear War, the hatchlings were left vulnerable in their nesting grounds, a &lt;a href=\"Underground%20Wyrm%20Cavern\"&gt;cave&lt;/a&gt; branching off from the &lt;a href=\"Underground%20River\"&gt;Underground River&lt;/a&gt; that ran beneath &lt;a href=\"Dragonspear%20Castle\"&gt;Dragonspear Castle&lt;/a&gt;. A malevolent wizard named Ithtaerus found the eggs and began experimenting on them, exposing them to black magic in the egg. This corrupted them into twisted monsters, a process accelerated by their being trapped so deep underground, and they became ravenous, cannibalistic beasts.\nThe entrance to the wyrmlings' prison-lair is a secret door, disguised as a purplish crack in the wall. It is located in the central section of the &lt;a href=\"Underground%20River\"&gt;Underground River&lt;/a&gt; area. The &lt;a href=\"Journal%20of%20Ithtaerus\"&gt;Journal of Ithtaerus&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Gem\"&gt;Shadow Gem&lt;/a&gt; can be found inside as well."}
{"id": "53068", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=53068", "title": "Blind Albino Wyrmlings", "text": "Blind Albino Wyrmlings is a that may be encountered in \"\".\nAcquisition.\nThis quest can be gained either by entering the lair of the wyrms or by being warned about the screams in the walls by &lt;a href=\"Murs\"&gt;Murs&lt;/a&gt; if she is championed during &lt;a href=\"Murs%20and%20the%20Brigands\"&gt;Murs and the Brigands&lt;/a&gt;.\nWalkthrough.\nOnce entering the &lt;a href=\"Underground%20Wyrm%20Cavern\"&gt;Underground Wyrm Cavern&lt;/a&gt; through a pink crack in the rocks in the &lt;a href=\"Underground%20River\"&gt;Underground River&lt;/a&gt; area, the party will be immediately attacked by three &lt;a href=\"Blind%20Albino%20Wyrmling\"&gt;Blind Albino Wyrmling&lt;/a&gt;s, one of which carries an &lt;a href=\"Acid-Etched%20Dagger\"&gt;Acid-Etched Dagger&lt;/a&gt;. After killing them, a fourth wyrmling can be found in a smaller area in the back, and after killing that one, a companion may make an observation, but the quest will end.\nIn a crack in the wall of the last cavern, the &lt;a href=\"Journal%20of%20Ithtaerus\"&gt;Journal of Ithtaerus&lt;/a&gt; and a &lt;a href=\"Shadow%20Gem\"&gt;Shadow Gem&lt;/a&gt; may be found."}
{"id": "46568", "revid": "50459896", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=46568", "title": "Blind Priest", "text": "The Blind Priests are a group of enemy &lt;a href=\"Cleric\"&gt;clerics&lt;/a&gt; found in the &lt;a href=\"Beholder%20Hideout\"&gt;Beholder Hideout&lt;/a&gt; accessed via the &lt;a href=\"Pit%20of%20the%20Faithless\"&gt;Pit of the Faithless&lt;/a&gt; during the side quest, &lt;a href=\"Investigate%20and%20Destroy%20the%20Cult%20of%20the%20Eyeless\"&gt;Investigate and Destroy the Cult of the Eyeless&lt;/a&gt;.\nBlind Priests.\nAll five types of Blind Priest share a few things in common; they all are &lt;a href=\"Alignment\"&gt;lawful evil&lt;/a&gt;, human, male clerics. The entire group is worth .\nNone of the priests have been given names by the game developers, so they will be referred to by the Number from their Creature Codes, a summary of which, is outlined below:\nRelated Quests.\n&lt;a href=\"%23Top\"&gt;Back\u00a0to\u00a0the\u00a0Top&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa1\"&gt;Leader&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa3\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a03&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa4\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a04&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa5\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a05&lt;/a&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"%23Top\"&gt;Back\u00a0to\u00a0the\u00a0Top&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa1\"&gt;Leader&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa2\"&gt;Fighter&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa4\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a04&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa5\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a05&lt;/a&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"%23Top\"&gt;Back\u00a0to\u00a0the\u00a0Top&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa1\"&gt;Leader&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa2\"&gt;Fighter&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa3\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a03&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa5\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a05&lt;/a&gt;\n&lt;a href=\"%23Top\"&gt;Back\u00a0to\u00a0the\u00a0Top&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa1\"&gt;Leader&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa2\"&gt;Fighter&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa3\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a03&lt;/a&gt;\u00a0\u00a0|\u00a0\u00a0&lt;a href=\"%23BraiWa4\"&gt;Blind\u00a0Priest\u00a04&lt;/a&gt;"}
{"id": "15688", "revid": "53053884", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=15688", "title": "Blinded", "text": "Blinded is a &lt;a href=\"Status%20Effects\"&gt;status effect&lt;/a&gt; which significantly lowers a creature's visual range. Depending on the game edition it causes:\nBut the main interest is the effect on visual range, which plummets to 2 from the default of 14. That a blinded creature can barely see anything means they can hardly target anything either, making them much easier prey. It is one of the status effects least resisted by enemies in the game. \nBlindness also prevents enemies from using vision-based attacks, for example the gaze attacks of &lt;a href=\"Basilisk\"&gt;Basilisk&lt;/a&gt;s or a &lt;a href=\"Beholder\"&gt;Beholder&lt;/a&gt;'s eye rays.\nBlindness can be inflicted by the spells &lt;a href=\"Blindness\"&gt;Blindness&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Prismatic%20Spray\"&gt;Prismatic Spray&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Glitterdust\"&gt;Glitterdust&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Holy%20Smite\"&gt;Holy Smite&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Sol%27s%20Searing%20Orb\"&gt;Sol's Searing Orb&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Sunray\"&gt;Sunray&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Nature%27s%20Beauty\"&gt;Nature's Beauty&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Power%20Word%2C%20Blind\"&gt;Power Word, Blind&lt;/a&gt;. It can also be caused by the special attack of the &lt;a href=\"Smoke%20Mephit\"&gt;Smoke Mephit&lt;/a&gt;.\nMagic Resistance and &lt;a href=\"Protection%20From%20Magic\"&gt;Protection From Magic&lt;/a&gt; can prevent all the above effects. &lt;a href=\"Spell%20Immunity\"&gt;Spell Immunity&lt;/a&gt; can prevent Blindness and Nature's Beauty\u00a0if cast with\u00a0immunity:\u00a0Illusion, Holy Smite if cast with immunity:\u00a0Necromancy, Sunray if cast with immunity:\u00a0Evocation, and Power Word Blind if cast with immunity:\u00a0Conjuration. &lt;a href=\"Potion%20of%20Magic%20Blocking\"&gt;Potion of Magic Blocking&lt;/a&gt; can prevent the effects of Blindness, Holy Smite and Sunray.\nIf affected, one can cure the Blinded effect with &lt;a href=\"Cure%20Disease\"&gt;Cure Disease&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Neutralize%20Poison\"&gt;Neutralize Poison&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Remove%20Magic\"&gt;Remove Magic&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=\"Heal\"&gt;Heal&lt;/a&gt; and Protection From Magic. Potion of Magic Blocking can remove the Blinded effect of Blindness, Holy Smite and Sunray."}
