{"id": "28980", "revid": "773742", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=28980", "title": "Wraith", "text": "A Wraith is an &lt;a href=\"undead\"&gt;undead&lt;/a&gt; creature of evil and darkness, hating the light and all living things. Wraiths can spawn randomly in any number of areas where other types of undead appear in the &lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s_Gate_%28game%29\"&gt;\"Baldur's Gate\"&lt;/a&gt; games, sometimes summoned by enemy Wizards or Priests.\nGameplay.\nWraiths are under a constant Blur overlay visual effect (does not grant the actual &lt;a href=\"Blur\"&gt;Blur&lt;/a&gt; spell abilities). \nThey can attack twice per round, inflicting 1d6 &lt;a href=\"Slashing%20damage\"&gt;Slashing damage&lt;/a&gt;; their attack weapon is considered a &lt;a href=\"Magical%20item\"&gt;magical&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=\"Enchanted%20item\"&gt;+4 weapon&lt;/a&gt; with a range of one foot, and &lt;a href=\"Speed%20Factor\"&gt;speed factor&lt;/a&gt; of zero.\nOn each successful hit upon the target, one Level is &lt;a href=\"Level%20drain\"&gt;drained&lt;/a&gt; (no saving throw). The attack bypasses &lt;a href=\"magic%20resistance\"&gt;magic resistance&lt;/a&gt;, and the effect cannot be &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;dispelled&lt;/a&gt;. However, lost levels can be &lt;a href=\"Lesser%20Restoration\"&gt;restored&lt;/a&gt;.\nNote.\nThe Wraith and &lt;a href=\"Greater%20Wraith\"&gt;Greater Wraith&lt;/a&gt; are not immune to &lt;a href=\"Poison\"&gt;Poison&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=\"Poison%20damage\"&gt;Poison damage&lt;/a&gt;. They are &lt;a href=\"Undead\"&gt;Undead&lt;/a&gt;, so this might be a miscoding in the creature file. No one knows for sure, but it is an aberration from the other game Undead creature files."}
{"id": "20219", "revid": "978785", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=20219", "title": "Wraith Form", "text": ""}
{"id": "52096", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=52096", "title": "Wraith Sarevok", "text": "Wraith Sarevok is a phantom or wraith-like embodiment of &lt;a href=\"Sarevok%20Anchev\"&gt;Sarevok Anchev&lt;/a&gt;, who was slain earlier in the first saga. This wraith will present the \"Test of Wrath\".\nGameplay.\nThe player's quest to collect the &lt;a href=\"Tears%20of%20Bhaal\"&gt;Tears of Bhaal&lt;/a&gt; during the various tests will pit Gorion's Ward against his old nemesis. This time it is in wraith form. The wraith will threaten, insult, cajole and goad you to unleash the very essence of Bhaal - by surrendering to the ultimate manifestation of retribution and murder - in &lt;a href=\"Slayer%20Form\"&gt;Slayer Form&lt;/a&gt;. The shade dares you to attack him, even after admitting his glee in destroying Gorion, and other atrocities.\nThere is much dialogue and rebuttal available with Sarevok the wraith. He even tells you:\nThe player must make a decision on which way to respond. Will the player harness the wrath within, or refuse it?\nIf the player decides to unleash the slayer, the wraith shouts:\nIf the player refuses the wraith it shouts:\nIn battle the Wraith Sarevok, he attacks as a competent, and highly magic resistant warrior. It will engage in melee the PC with its greatsword until one of you are destroyed. If the player prevails, then a on screen text message displays:\nDuring the battle with Sarevok, the player's party can join in and gang up on the vengeful creature - or the bhaalspawn can fight him solo, spawn versus spawn.\nNote.\nSarevok wants &lt;a href=\"Gorion%27s%20Ward\"&gt;Gorion's Ward&lt;/a&gt; to live up to the heritage of the Lord of Murder and change into the &lt;a href=\"Slayer%20Form\"&gt;Slayer Form&lt;/a&gt;. This action is allowed as the player desires. However, the slayer transformation isn't a requirement to complete the Tear of Bhaal test. It is entirely optional. Regardless of what choices are made in the encounter with Wraith Sarevok, it will result in a fight to the death. The only way to obtain the Tear of Bhaal here is to destroy Wraith Sarevok.\nMod content.\nInstallation of the &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Coast%20Stratagems\"&gt;Sword Coast Stratagems&lt;/a&gt; Mod makes some minor revisions, including a warrior based SCS AI script for better tactical behavior. The creature is scripted to use/consume three random SCS supplied potions for healing or boosting abilities during combat."}
{"id": "14630", "revid": "50459896", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=14630", "title": "Wraith Spider", "text": "The Wraith Spider is one of three different high-level &lt;a href=\"Spiders\"&gt;Spiders&lt;/a&gt; encountered in the original \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\", the other two being the &lt;a href=\"Phase%20Spider\"&gt;Phase Spider&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=\"Sword%20Spider\"&gt;Sword Spider&lt;/a&gt;.\nDescription.\nThey are fairly rare, usually only found within the depths of forests, and are distinguishable from their brethren by way of a yellow body with dark-purple legs.\nDespite the name \"wraith\" they are classified as monsters, not undead.\nGameplay.\nLike most spiders, they are immune to &lt;a href=\"webbed\"&gt;webs&lt;/a&gt;, yet lack the gradual &lt;a href=\"poison\"&gt;poison&lt;/a&gt; that most other spiders are known for.\nIt is immune to normal weapons, charm, confusion, hold, sleep, and many other effects and spells, making it quite a challenge for low-level parties (see Special \"Effects\" in the InfoBox, right).\nBesides doing 1d6 &lt;a href=\"Piercing%20damage\"&gt;piercing&lt;/a&gt; damage on a successful attack, the target must &lt;a href=\"Saving%20throw\"&gt;save vs. spell&lt;/a&gt; to negate a &lt;a href=\"Strength\"&gt;Strength&lt;/a&gt; drain of 5 points. Each drain is temporary; 300 seconds (i.e., 5 minutes). However, the effect is cumulative, such that the target will instantly die if strength is drained below 1 point."}
{"id": "29222", "revid": "3234315", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=29222", "title": "Wraith spiders", "text": ""}
{"id": "12137", "revid": "44830706", "url": "https://baldursgate.fandom.com/wiki?curid=12137", "title": "Wraithform", "text": "When Wraithform is cast, the wizard and all of his gear become insubstantial.\nGameplay.\nThe caster applies this spell to self only.\nWhen the spell is finished, the caster's sprite will display several visual effects such as a transparency fade and glow pulse effect for the duration of the spell. A sound effect is audible at the beginning and another when the spell expires. The creature's portrait will display an icon (No. 23 \"Invulnerable\").\nAlso, after the spell is cast a text display reads \"Wraithformed\".\nThe spell now will protect against all normal weapons (including missile ammunition). Obviously any magical or enchanted weapon will be able to bypass this protection.\nAdditionally, the spell also boosts the caster's &lt;a href=\"Magical%20damage\"&gt;Magical damage&lt;/a&gt; resistance by +25%, which is cumulative with other sources of magic damage resistance.\nThe spell deactivates arcane and divine spellcasting and also innate abilities (e.g. Bhaalspawn powers). Scrolls can still be used to cast spells in this wraithform.\nThis spell can be removed with any &lt;a href=\"Dispel%20Magic\"&gt;Dispel Magic&lt;/a&gt; effect, but it is immune to the &lt;a href=\"Breach\"&gt;Breach&lt;/a&gt; spell.\nIt appears that this spell can be \"stacked\", as it doesn't have the required coding to prevent that. If two of these spells were applied to the same caster, they would be able to receive additional magical damage resistance. Perhaps the developers missed fixing this issue, as similar spells were revised to prevent such things. Of course, since this form restricts Wizard spell casting, it would need to be applied with a scroll.\nAcquisition.\n In the original , Wraith Form \u2013 as it is spelled in those \u2013 is only available in the base game, \"&lt;a href=\"Baldur%27s%20Gate%20%28game%29\"&gt;Baldur's Gate&lt;/a&gt;\", as rare &lt;a href=\"random%20treasure\"&gt;random treasure&lt;/a&gt;. This find is replaced with a &lt;a href=\"Spell%20scrolls\"&gt;scroll&lt;/a&gt; for \"&lt;a href=\"Dire%20Charm\"&gt;Dire Charm&lt;/a&gt;\" when the add-on ' is installed or in packages, such as the ', and the &lt;a href=\"spell\"&gt;spell&lt;/a&gt; is completely removed from the series' second part \u2013 probably due to buggy behavior.\n In the ' and its expansion ', the scroll can only be found during a single encounter, making the spell otherwise available for a &lt;a href=\"mage\"&gt;mage&lt;/a&gt; only if &lt;a href=\"Character%20generation\"&gt;creating a new character&lt;/a&gt; for the add-on campaign.\u00a0The scroll is sold at three stores in \"\".\nTrivia.\nThe Advanced Dungeons and Dragons 2nd Edition Wizard spell \"Wraithform\" differs significantly from the one implemented in the BG game. For instance, the wizard can pass through small holes or narrow openings, even mere cracks, with all he wears or holds in his hands, as long as the spell persists. Additionally, no form of attack is possible when in wraithform, except against creatures that exist on the Ethereal Plane, where all attacks (both ways) are normal. See the External link for further reading.\nMod content.\n&lt;a href=\"Spell%20Revisions\"&gt;Spell Revisions&lt;/a&gt; mod has changed this arcane spell, revising its school and internal Opcode structure:\nWraithform\nAlteration\nLevel: 3\nRange: 0\nDuration: 2 rounds/level\nCasting Time: 1\nArea of Effect: The caster\nSaving Throw: None\nWhen this spell is cast, the wizard and all of &lt;PRO_HISHER&gt; gear become insubstantial. The caster is subject only to magical or special attacks, including those by weapons of +1 or better enchantment, or by creatures otherwise able to affect those struck only by magical weapons. The wizard also gains 25% resistance to magic damage. While in wraithform, the caster cannot cast either arcane or divine spells."}
